  "timeframe": "15m (execution) / 4H (bias)",
  "market_context": "ETH 4-hour candle failed to close over the previous 4-hour high, signaling a failure to displace. This established bearish bias targeting the previous 4-hour low. A new 4-hour candle then opened and price began dropping into a fair value gap array.",
  "key_observation": "When the 4H candle fails to displace over the previous 4H high, bias shifts toward the previous 4H low; the 15-minute timeframe can be used as the execution timeframe via a fair value gap entry.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified on the 4H that the prior candle failed to displace/close over the previous 4-hour high, giving bearish bias toward the previous 4-hour low.",
    "Step 2: Dropped to the 15-minute timeframe as the execution timeframe, marking the open of the new 4H candle.",
    "Step 3: Observed price open and begin dropping into a fair value gap array on the sell side.",
    "Step 4: Identified a freshly formed 15-minute fair value gap as the entry POI (entry at start of FVG, alternatively at consequent encroachment).",
    "Step 5: Placed stop above the high of the FVG and target at the previous 4-hour low, yielding 2.3R.",
    "Step 6: Let the trade play out — price traveled from one side of the range to the other, reaching target."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade reached target at the previous 4-hour low, achieving 2.3R.",
  "lessons": "Higher timeframe failure to displace gives directional bias; lower timeframes (15m here) can be used as execution timeframes with FVG entries. These concepts are fractal — the same logic applies on weekly down to 5-minute charts.",
